04433nam a22005775i 9780773553682DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2018377314  a97807735536827 a10.1515/97807735536822doi  a(DE-B1597)657323  a(OCoLC)1032000265  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aDG738.14.M4bJ86 2018 4aDG738.14.M4b.J864 2018 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a945.510709242231 aJungić, Josephine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGiuliano de' Medici :bMachiavelli’s Prince in Life and Art /cJosephine Jungić. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b40 colour images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tFlorence and the Medici -- tGiuliano and His Venetian Friends -- tGiuliano and Cesare Borgia -- tGiuliano and Machiavelli -- tGiuliano, Capo of Florence -- tGiuliano and the Boscoli-Capponi Conspiracy -- tGiuliano and Leonardo da Vinci -- tGiuliano as Machiavelli's Il Principe -- tRaphael's Portrait of Giuliano as Machiavelli's New Prince -- tDeath and Burial -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost modern historians perpetuate the myth that Giuliano de' Medici (1479–1516), son of Lorenzo the Magnificent, was nothing more than an inconsequential, womanizing hedonist with little inclination or ability for politics. In the first sustained biography of this misrepresented figure, Josephine Jungic re-evaluates Giuliano’s life and shows that his infamous reputation was exaggerated by Medici partisans who feared his popularity and respect for republican self-rule. Rejecting the autocratic rule imposed by his nephew, Lorenzo (Duke of Urbino), and brother, Giovanni (Pope Leo X), Giuliano advocated restraint and retention of republican traditions, believing his family should be “first among equals” and not more. As a result, the family and those closest to them wrote him out of the political scene, and historians – relying too heavily upon the accounts of supporters of Cardinal Giovanni and the Medici regime – followed suit. Interpreting works of art, books, and letters as testimony, Jungic constructs a new narrative to demonstrate that Giuliano was loved and admired by some of the most talented and famous men of his day, including Cesare Borgia, Michelangelo Buonarroti, Niccolò Machiavelli, Leonardo da Vinci, and Raphael. More than a political biography, this volume offers a refreshing look at a man who was a significant patron and ally of intellectuals, artists, and religious reformers, revealing Giuliano to be at the heart of the period’s most significant cultural accomplishments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedici, Giuliano de',-duca di Nemours,-1479-1516-Friends and associates. 0aMedici, Giuliano de',-duca di Nemours,-1479-1516. 0aMedici, House of. 0aNobilityzItalyzFlorencevBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355368240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773553682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773553682/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles